<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="context-cols">
      <div class="context-text">
        <p class="sl">Riverside County Appliance Context</p>
        <h2>Riverside County appliance patterns by area</h2>
        <p>The Temecula–Murrieta corridor is one of the fastest-growing residential markets in Southern California. A large proportion of homes built after 2010 — consistent Samsung, LG, and GE packages hitting their first major maintenance cycle. First-time homeowners dealing with first appliance failures are a significant part of our Temecula and Murrieta calls.</p>
        <p>Corona and Norco, closer to the LA Basin, have housing spanning from 1970s ranch homes to 2000s construction. The western wind corridor through Cajon Pass creates unique dust conditions — condenser coils in homes along the pass accumulate debris faster than typical inland environments. Our technicians check coil condition early on any refrigeration call in this area.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="context-facts">
        <div class="cfact"><h4>🍷 Temecula wine country — luxury appliances</h4><p>Sub-Zero, Wolf, and Thermador in Temecula estates. Cooler climate than the flatland IE but still hot summers.</p></div>
        <div class="cfact"><h4>🏗️ Fast-growing new construction market</h4><p>Murrieta, Menifee, and Lake Elsinore — large 2010–2020 construction now entering the repair window.</p></div>
        <div class="cfact"><h4>🌡️ Extreme inland heat (Moreno Valley, Hemet)</h4><p>Among the hottest communities in SoCal. Refrigeration stress is significant May through October.</p></div>
        <div class="cfact"><h4>💨 Western pass wind (Corona, Norco)</h4><p>Wind corridor from Cajon Pass carries debris. Condenser coils clog faster than typical IE conditions.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
